00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:04,000
Downloaded From www.AllSubs.org

1
00:00:23,320 --> 00:00:29,634
Dear Wendy, I'm writing to tell you
the story about the two of us-

2
00:00:29,720 --> 00:00:34,874
- as I saw it, but never had the
nerve to tell you face to face.

3
00:00:36,280 --> 00:00:40,558
Maybe things would have gone
differently if I had told you then.

4
00:00:40,640 --> 00:00:44,428
And maybe things would not
have to end this way.

5
00:00:48,480 --> 00:00:51,756
I've lived in Electric Park Square
all my life.

6
00:00:52,040 --> 00:00:56,397
And all my life the wheel from
the elevator tower was creaking.

7
00:00:56,480 --> 00:01:00,632
We called it the Ferris wheel.

8
00:01:00,720 --> 00:01:06,829
But now, as I write this
I can't see the square, -

9
00:01:07,120 --> 00:01:10,749
- and I can't hear the creaking.

10
00:01:11,040 --> 00:01:15,830
And worst of all
I do not have you next to me.

11
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:26,639
OK, Susan...

12
00:01:26,720 --> 00:01:30,759
Here are your round-nosed
full metal jackets.

13
00:01:32,840 --> 00:01:38,153
Freddie, these are yours.
I got hollow-point expanders. 32s.

14
00:02:36,800 --> 00:02:39,837
I was stubborn as a child.

15
00:02:40,120 --> 00:02:45,831
My dad thought it was a forgone
conclusion I'd work in the mine.

16
00:02:45,920 --> 00:02:49,276
I think a week went by
with the same ritual.

17
00:02:49,360 --> 00:02:52,909
Down in the morning
with him hot-tempered as usual.

18
00:02:59,520 --> 00:03:04,878
Then up again, because
I refused to get off the elevator.

19
00:03:05,160 --> 00:03:10,996
And up to Clarabelle, who'd be
waiting every day to take me home.

20
00:03:13,880 --> 00:03:20,877
Clarabelle was our maid. She battled
Dad's decisions tooth and nail.

21
00:03:21,160 --> 00:03:27,269
She'd say her little boy was
far too sensitive for the mine.

22
00:03:27,360 --> 00:03:30,955
Too weak
with those skinny arms of his.

23
00:03:34,800 --> 00:03:41,672
He had an imagination. And one day
his ideas would save the world.

24
00:03:41,760 --> 00:03:44,832
She had no doubt about that.

25
00:03:44,920 --> 00:03:47,229
Dicky!

26
00:03:50,400 --> 00:03:54,837
...with that rifle he pulls the
trigger on a pair of underwear.

27
00:03:56,400 --> 00:04:00,188
- No!
- Thought he had about a 10 point...

28
00:04:06,400 --> 00:04:09,756
- Hey there...
- Dick.

29
00:04:10,040 --> 00:04:14,511
Richard.
Hey, honey, how you doin'?

30
00:04:14,600 --> 00:04:17,512
Two chocolate donuts, please.

31
00:04:17,600 --> 00:04:21,639
We bought an Aunt Maple's
chocolate muffin every morning.

32
00:04:21,720 --> 00:04:25,713
"That's the one
you like the best, Dicky."

33
00:04:25,800 --> 00:04:29,395
Aunt Maple's
special chocolate muffin.

34
00:04:29,480 --> 00:04:32,631
- I'm passionate about 'em.
- So did Sheriff Krugsby.

35
00:04:32,720 --> 00:04:36,759
Thank you for my bag, Mr Salomon.
Good day, Sheriff.

36
00:04:36,840 --> 00:04:39,752
Good day, Clarabelle. Richard...

37
00:04:40,040 --> 00:04:45,194
All right, Howard. A bag
for my early-morning lollipop.

38
00:04:49,160 --> 00:04:54,518
Dad gave in after a week.
I escaped the clutches of the mine.

39
00:04:54,600 --> 00:04:58,798
But before you ask why
I keep talking about Clarabelle...

40
00:04:58,880 --> 00:05:02,429
Well
she's the reason we met, Wendy.

41
00:05:04,320 --> 00:05:09,394
Clarabelle got me a job at Salomon's.
That it was better for my fantasy, -

42
00:05:09,480 --> 00:05:13,598
- or helped to inspire me to save
the world was difficult to see.

43
00:05:13,680 --> 00:05:17,355
I stocked shelves with a
strange fellow named Stevie.

44
00:05:17,440 --> 00:05:21,718
He never said a word, and
he didn't work in the mine either.

45
00:05:21,800 --> 00:05:24,712
He claimed he was too tall.

46
00:05:24,800 --> 00:05:30,272
Mr Salomon owned the supermarket.
He always looked very worried.

47
00:05:30,360 --> 00:05:34,876
He was afraid of armed robbery
and spoke often of the gangs, -

48
00:05:34,960 --> 00:05:38,157
- but I'd never seen them.

49
00:05:38,240 --> 00:05:40,754
I'm hyperventilating.

50
00:05:44,440 --> 00:05:48,877
It's all right.
Don't worry about it.

51
00:05:49,160 --> 00:05:53,199
Sorry.
Don't worry, I'll ring these up.

52
00:05:54,560 --> 00:05:59,793
Go to your room, put on your white
shirt. Mind you don't wrinkle it.

53
00:05:59,880 --> 00:06:04,715
And your tie. You're going to
Sebastian's birthday party.

54
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:06,433
I don't want to.

55
00:06:06,520 --> 00:06:09,592
Sebastian was
exceptionally irritating.

56
00:06:09,680 --> 00:06:12,877
Why Clarabelle made me go
was a mystery.

57
00:06:13,160 --> 00:06:16,789
He did a particularly annoying
thing with his eyebrows.

58
00:06:16,880 --> 00:06:20,316
- Go and get him a nice present.
- Why?

59
00:06:20,400 --> 00:06:25,793
- Because you'll make new friends.
- I have friends.

60
00:06:26,080 --> 00:06:29,595
Who is your friends?

61
00:06:31,640 --> 00:06:34,438
- Come here, Dicky.
- I'm not going.

62
00:06:37,680 --> 00:06:41,275
Come on now...

63
00:06:42,320 --> 00:06:45,198
Come on, put your arms around me.

64
00:06:45,280 --> 00:06:50,673
There was no fighting Clarabelle.
I had to get the idiot a present.

65
00:06:50,760 --> 00:06:53,274
Hey, D! Over here!

66
00:06:53,360 --> 00:06:58,753
Huey got his leg braces that day.
He lived behind the square.

67
00:06:59,040 --> 00:07:02,316
He had virtually no legs.
You got them?

68
00:07:02,400 --> 00:07:05,119
Yeah, I did.

69
00:07:05,200 --> 00:07:10,513
Now Freddie won't get beaten up for
having a brother in a wheelchair.

70
00:07:10,600 --> 00:07:14,388
- They cost 7000 bucks.
- Freddie! 700.

71
00:07:14,480 --> 00:07:17,790
Freddie always exaggerated tenfold.

72
00:07:17,880 --> 00:07:23,876
By the way, he got beat up more
once his brother used the braces.

73
00:07:24,160 --> 00:07:27,869
Anyway, I had to buy a present
for that brat Sebastian.

74
00:07:27,960 --> 00:07:32,112
- Catch you later.
- See you, Dick.

75
00:07:32,200 --> 00:07:36,478
- Why tell everyone I got beat up?
- They already know.

76
00:07:36,560 --> 00:07:39,870
No one knows.

77
00:07:39,960 --> 00:07:42,599
It looks like you got
a crutch up your ass.

78
00:08:01,120 --> 00:08:06,148
- What do you want?
- To buy something.

79
00:08:06,240 --> 00:08:09,198
What?

80
00:08:09,280 --> 00:08:11,077
A present.

81
00:08:13,720 --> 00:08:16,712
- Who is it for?
- An idiot.

82
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:20,515
- A guy or a girl?
- A guy.

83
00:08:20,600 --> 00:08:25,549
Her name was Susan. She smelled
just like her mom's lousy store.

84
00:08:25,640 --> 00:08:30,634
We'd gone to the same school.

85
00:08:30,720 --> 00:08:34,759
Susan had never gotten breasts
like the other girls at school.

86
00:08:34,840 --> 00:08:40,631
- What about the toy gun?
- It's been there for a century.

87
00:08:40,720 --> 00:08:43,314
So what?

88
00:08:43,400 --> 00:08:46,870
I think it's kind of pretty.

89
00:08:47,160 --> 00:08:51,711
- Can I see it?
- Yeah... I suppose.

90
00:08:57,600 --> 00:09:02,754
Such a shitty present would serve
Sebastian right. It wasn't even new.

91
00:09:03,040 --> 00:09:06,828
It had a burn mark
on the side of the stock.

92
00:09:07,120 --> 00:09:11,079
He would hate this present.
I couldn't wait to give it to him.

93
00:09:14,400 --> 00:09:19,838
That's a nice present for Sebastian.
He always pretends he's shooting.

94
00:09:20,120 --> 00:09:24,238
- He's gonna love it.
- You think so?

95
00:09:25,640 --> 00:09:30,794
I began to wonder about the present.
There were too many weapons.

96
00:09:30,880 --> 00:09:34,873
Besides, I was a pacifist.
How could I forget that?

97
00:09:34,960 --> 00:09:39,829
It would be wrong to give a boy a
gun. What would he grow up into?

98
00:09:40,120 --> 00:09:42,554
Keep your tie on!

99
00:09:42,640 --> 00:09:48,112
So I decided to give Sebastian a
book: "The Picture of Dorian Gray".

100
00:09:48,200 --> 00:09:52,478
Abridged, since someone had torn
out the last 20 pages. No matter.

101
00:09:52,560 --> 00:09:55,393
I'd gotten it cheap.

102
00:09:55,480 --> 00:10:01,828
But Sebastian didn't open it
so I didn't see his disappointment.

103
00:10:02,120 --> 00:10:07,717
He didn't like the toy gun.
Can I have my money back?

104
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:11,197
We don't do returns.

105
00:10:12,800 --> 00:10:15,678
Oh... OK.

106
00:10:25,960 --> 00:10:29,555
- Bye.
- Bye.

107
00:10:29,640 --> 00:10:35,397
I wanted to throw the toy gun away
immediately, but I didn't.

108
00:10:35,480 --> 00:10:39,155
It felt smooth and nice
in my pocket.

109
00:11:03,800 --> 00:11:09,716
Some years later my dad died after
a temper tantrum in the mine.

110
00:11:09,800 --> 00:11:13,190
I didn't mind too much
since I never really knew him.

111
00:11:21,280 --> 00:11:24,750
Richard, I'm really sorry.

112
00:11:26,560 --> 00:11:31,156
You're going to be all right.
We'll all keep an eye out on you.

113
00:11:43,160 --> 00:11:47,199
With Mom having died years ago
I was alone for real.

114
00:11:47,280 --> 00:11:51,796
I was a real loser, like everyone
else who didn't work in the mine.

115
00:11:52,080 --> 00:11:56,392
I stayed in Electric Park
with what my father left me.

116
00:11:56,480 --> 00:12:00,632
Mostly loose doorframes
after his door-slamming.

117
00:12:00,720 --> 00:12:06,636
And Clarabelle quit.
She was really quite old now.

118
00:12:06,720 --> 00:12:11,191
While I was tidying up
I came across the toy gun again.

119
00:12:12,400 --> 00:12:16,951
And that was it, Wendy.
That was where it all started.

120
00:12:41,480 --> 00:12:45,678
I thought you said
you were a pacifist?

121
00:12:45,760 --> 00:12:50,038
Perhaps I did
but it's just an old toy gun.

122
00:12:51,880 --> 00:12:55,190
It's not a toy.

123
00:12:55,280 --> 00:12:59,159
It's a 6.65 mm
double action revolver.

124
00:13:04,320 --> 00:13:08,711
- Are you sure?
- Yeah.

125
00:13:36,560 --> 00:13:38,869
Who is it?

126
00:13:49,440 --> 00:13:52,318
Hi, Stevie. Nice to see you.

127
00:13:55,760 --> 00:13:58,911
- Can I come in?
- Sure.

128
00:14:00,720 --> 00:14:03,792
- Can I sit?
- Yeah.

129
00:14:11,680 --> 00:14:16,549
So...
Is everything all right?

130
00:14:16,640 --> 00:14:19,677
Yeah. Uhm...

131
00:14:19,760 --> 00:14:23,753
- I need to show you something.
- OK.

132
00:14:33,320 --> 00:14:38,872
This is a 7.63 mm
model 1896 broom-handle -

133
00:14:38,960 --> 00:14:42,669
- from the battle of El Alamein.

134
00:14:42,760 --> 00:14:46,514
It belonged to one of
Rommel's tank commanders, -

135
00:14:46,600 --> 00:14:48,511
- but it didn't serve him well.

136
00:14:48,600 --> 00:14:54,835
When the allies attacked, he tried
to rally petrified Italian deserters.

137
00:14:54,920 --> 00:14:59,516
He wanted to set an example
and execute the Italian sergeant.

138
00:14:59,600 --> 00:15:04,469
But it misfired. Didn't shoot.

139
00:15:04,560 --> 00:15:08,872
So they locked him in a destroyed
tank and left him in the sun.

140
00:15:09,160 --> 00:15:14,359
My grandfather found the
baked body two weeks later, -

141
00:15:14,440 --> 00:15:17,876
- the treacherous gun
still in his hands.

142
00:15:24,400 --> 00:15:27,631
Really?

143
00:15:29,400 --> 00:15:34,838
- That's really something, huh?
- I got something for you, too.

144
00:15:35,120 --> 00:15:37,509
What is it?

145
00:15:41,360 --> 00:15:47,595
It's for your gun. I made it myself.
I found an old casing.

146
00:15:49,440 --> 00:15:54,912
I thought maybe you'd want to try
shooting your gun. Just for fun.

147
00:16:02,040 --> 00:16:04,315
OK.

148
00:16:04,400 --> 00:16:08,473
- Come on then.
- Now?

149
00:16:08,560 --> 00:16:10,869
All right.

150
00:16:15,440 --> 00:16:20,753
Hey, I'm a pacifist too.
I'd never dream of shooting anyone.

151
00:16:20,840 --> 00:16:24,071
Of course not.

152
00:16:29,600 --> 00:16:33,149
- This way. To the old mine.
- OK.

153
00:16:48,080 --> 00:16:52,198
I followed Stevie through
the closed-down part of the mine.

154
00:16:52,280 --> 00:16:55,875
It was dangerous there.

155
00:16:56,160 --> 00:16:59,789
But we went down to
some old, forgotten shaft.

156
00:17:00,080 --> 00:17:03,470
You have to be really quiet.

157
00:17:13,200 --> 00:17:15,839
- Down there?
- Straight down.

158
00:17:16,120 --> 00:17:19,430
- Is it all right?
- Totally safe.

159
00:17:26,440 --> 00:17:30,274
- Haven't you been here before?
- No.

160
00:17:30,360 --> 00:17:34,831
I'm not crazy about the mines.

161
00:17:34,920 --> 00:17:38,117
You don't go out much, do you?

162
00:17:38,200 --> 00:17:42,796
Never do that! Always
keep your firearm pointed down.

163
00:17:43,080 --> 00:17:46,595
- Pointed down?
- At all times.

164
00:17:46,680 --> 00:17:49,797
What I'm gonna do now, -

165
00:17:50,080 --> 00:17:56,155
- I'll pull this lever and open up
the chamber. There it is.

166
00:17:56,240 --> 00:18:00,916
I'm going to take the cartridge
and place it right there...

167
00:18:16,960 --> 00:18:21,351
Wow! OK...

168
00:18:27,080 --> 00:18:31,710
A bull's eye.
On your very first shot.

169
00:18:32,000 --> 00:18:35,515
I couldn't even do that
with Bad Steel.

170
00:18:36,880 --> 00:18:38,836
What did you say?

171
00:18:39,120 --> 00:18:43,875
Bad Steel.
That's what I call it.

172
00:18:43,960 --> 00:18:49,193
General Patton named his revolver.
I thought it was kind of cool.

173
00:18:51,640 --> 00:18:56,191
God, yours is so tiny!
It's like a little lady's gun.

174
00:18:56,280 --> 00:19:00,193
- You're right.
- You should give it a girl's name.

175
00:19:09,840 --> 00:19:12,559
Wendy.

176
00:19:13,960 --> 00:19:16,997
I'll call it Wendy.

177
00:19:20,560 --> 00:19:23,597
It's perfect.

178
00:19:29,280 --> 00:19:33,193
Suddenly, I was one of
those people with guns.

179
00:19:33,280 --> 00:19:38,400
With a scary, bad conscience
I touched the gun that night.

180
00:19:38,480 --> 00:19:45,318
Guns made the world an evil place.
But I couldn't get rid of it.

181
00:19:45,400 --> 00:19:49,518
Not even back when I thought
it wasn't dangerous.

182
00:19:49,600 --> 00:19:52,751
And now you were mine.

183
00:19:52,840 --> 00:19:56,150
Because it is you I'm referring to.

184
00:19:56,240 --> 00:20:01,189
It was as though you, a gun
were trying to tell me something.

185
00:20:01,280 --> 00:20:05,273
Something I did not yet understand.

186
00:20:05,360 --> 00:20:11,595
One thing was sure, Wendy.
I had found a new friend.

187
00:20:11,680 --> 00:20:15,389
And it was you.

188
00:20:18,080 --> 00:20:21,755
Dear Wendy
it's your sensitive friend again, -

189
00:20:21,840 --> 00:20:25,594
- who, in his ecstasy of meeting
you, has dug out his old music.

190
00:20:25,680 --> 00:20:27,989
The Zombies.

191
00:20:31,520 --> 00:20:35,513
Well, no one told me about her

192
00:20:35,600 --> 00:20:38,831
the way she lied

193
00:20:38,920 --> 00:20:45,268
no one told me about her
how many people cried

194
00:20:45,360 --> 00:20:48,716
but it's too late
to say you're sorry

195
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:52,754
how would I know
why should I care?

196
00:20:53,040 --> 00:20:57,511
Please don't bother trying
to find her, she's not there

197
00:20:59,160 --> 00:21:05,315
let me tell you about the way she
looks, the way she acts

198
00:21:05,400 --> 00:21:08,551
her voice is soft and cool
her eyes are clear and bright

199
00:21:08,640 --> 00:21:11,393
but she's not there

200
00:21:13,240 --> 00:21:16,755
- Stevie! They could set dogs on us.
- No, relax.

201
00:21:16,840 --> 00:21:19,798
We should keep a safe distance
to avoid stuff like that.

202
00:21:20,080 --> 00:21:23,038
It's not a problem.
Let's just shoot.

203
00:21:26,840 --> 00:21:30,628
Stevie and I had found each other
in this dark, secret passion.

204
00:21:30,720 --> 00:21:34,759
He was a technical genius.
And we kept reading.

205
00:21:34,840 --> 00:21:38,150
Stevie about the metal
me about the shooting.

206
00:21:38,240 --> 00:21:43,712
Like why an exit wound
says everything about a shot, -

207
00:21:43,800 --> 00:21:48,396
- and about a weapon
and its potential. Or its "soul".

208
00:21:48,480 --> 00:21:50,869
Stevie and I actually started
talking a little bit.

209
00:21:51,160 --> 00:21:55,233
Good velocity.
Causes immediate incapacitation.

210
00:21:55,320 --> 00:21:59,632
And luckily I had you now, Wendy.
Every second of the day.

211
00:22:00,800 --> 00:22:05,635
We started carrying. You and
Bad Steel lay in our pockets.

212
00:22:05,720 --> 00:22:08,632
It felt important and reassuring.

213
00:22:08,720 --> 00:22:13,953
The two of you made us grow.
Even Mr Salomon was impressed.

214
00:22:19,200 --> 00:22:22,875
I can't take it anymore...

215
00:22:22,960 --> 00:22:25,713
It's all...

216
00:22:27,200 --> 00:22:31,751
They say gangs are completely
out of hand in town.

217
00:22:31,840 --> 00:22:34,400
And...

218
00:22:42,680 --> 00:22:47,151
Maybe I'm overreacting.
I don't know.

219
00:22:47,240 --> 00:22:50,391
What do you think, Dick?

220
00:22:53,280 --> 00:22:59,879
I must say Clarabelle guessed right.
You've really come around.

221
00:22:59,960 --> 00:23:06,672
You walk with confidence, you look
folks in the eye at the checkout.

222
00:23:07,800 --> 00:23:12,271
I like that. It breeds respect.
More maybe than a gun would.

223
00:23:13,400 --> 00:23:17,837
He made me assistant manager
and would have given me a raise.

224
00:23:19,920 --> 00:23:25,870
Stevie was a better man, too.
He took a loan and bought a van.

225
00:23:25,960 --> 00:23:30,238
He had his own company and could
look people in the eye too.

226
00:23:30,320 --> 00:23:34,154
Stevie. Congratulations.

227
00:23:34,240 --> 00:23:37,118
- You finally got it.
- Thanks, Dick.

228
00:23:40,480 --> 00:23:45,235
We'd stopped sneaking along when
the real men came up from the mine.

229
00:23:45,320 --> 00:23:48,392
We were just as good as them.

230
00:23:48,480 --> 00:23:54,476
Electric Park Square was just as
much ours. All the zones we named:

231
00:23:54,560 --> 00:23:58,872
The Slope Corner, The Shack
Way Out, East Side, -

232
00:23:59,160 --> 00:24:02,675
- Center Pole, Shopside
The Swamp, -

233
00:24:02,760 --> 00:24:07,231
- where the water always rose
from the drains. Slong Island.

234
00:24:07,320 --> 00:24:13,236
And Salomon's. It was all just
as much ours now. If not more.

235
00:24:40,080 --> 00:24:42,435
I need this slice from you.

236
00:25:15,400 --> 00:25:19,473
In a way it's a shame
we're keeping this to ourselves.

237
00:25:19,560 --> 00:25:21,790
What do you mean?

238
00:25:22,080 --> 00:25:25,789
Pacifists with guns is
such a great idea, -

239
00:25:26,080 --> 00:25:29,755
- it's practically our duty
to share it with others.

240
00:25:30,040 --> 00:25:34,989
- Like who?
- Like the people who need it.

241
00:25:36,480 --> 00:25:38,277
OK...

242
00:25:38,360 --> 00:25:43,832
We were losers.
Maybe not right now, but we were.

243
00:25:45,160 --> 00:25:50,439
That's right. We were not the
only losers in Electric Park.

244
00:25:50,520 --> 00:25:54,559
Exactly.
That's exactly what I'm saying.

245
00:25:58,720 --> 00:26:01,757
- You need some help?
- No, I'm OK.

246
00:26:03,200 --> 00:26:07,591
- When is it?
- Five o'clock, old mine building.

247
00:26:07,680 --> 00:26:10,990
- You're gonna be there, right?
- Yeah.

248
00:26:14,960 --> 00:26:19,397
I'd have to ask permission
to get out of the store.

249
00:26:19,480 --> 00:26:23,871
Hey! It's over here! Right here!

250
00:26:24,160 --> 00:26:27,630
Stevie
let's find something they can sit on.

251
00:26:28,680 --> 00:26:34,232
It wasn't easy to get them out of
their shells, but there they were.

252
00:26:34,320 --> 00:26:39,838
By the old mine we had a meeting.
The losers from Electric Park.

253
00:26:39,920 --> 00:26:44,118
Susan!
Glad you could join us here.

254
00:26:44,200 --> 00:26:46,395
Hi, Freddie!

255
00:26:46,480 --> 00:26:52,191
Look at it as an experiment to help
you become what you really are.

256
00:27:00,800 --> 00:27:04,156
What's that?

257
00:27:05,720 --> 00:27:08,996
A whole lot happier, I expect.

258
00:27:12,560 --> 00:27:15,438
You guys in, or...?

259
00:27:15,520 --> 00:27:19,832
I think it's a good idea.
I mean, there's pacifichism...

260
00:27:19,920 --> 00:27:25,119
- It's good we don't shoot anybody.
- You mean pacifism.

261
00:27:25,200 --> 00:27:28,237
The Dandies was
the name I came up with.

262
00:27:28,320 --> 00:27:30,993
It had the cheerfulness
I was hoping for.

263
00:27:41,160 --> 00:27:45,472
Hey, guys!
Freddie found a hole.

264
00:27:45,560 --> 00:27:49,109
- Found a what?
- A trapdoor.

265
00:27:49,200 --> 00:27:52,715
I think it goes down to the mine.
Come on!

266
00:27:53,000 --> 00:27:55,878
- Looks good.
- Great.

267
00:27:57,360 --> 00:28:00,670
- They're coming!
- Are they coming?

268
00:28:00,760 --> 00:28:05,595
It's deep! Damn, it's deep! I think
it leads through all the mines.

269
00:28:07,200 --> 00:28:09,873
Come on, hurry!

270
00:28:09,960 --> 00:28:14,636
- Oh, my God, it's huge!
- What are we talking about here?

271
00:28:14,720 --> 00:28:18,713
The disused mine building became
what we later called The Temple.

272
00:28:18,800 --> 00:28:23,749
Freddie knew lots of other
abandoned mine shafts.

273
00:28:23,840 --> 00:28:28,834
One of them emerged in what
would become our living room.

274
00:28:28,920 --> 00:28:32,833
- Don't make too much noise.
- This is exactly 15 feet.

275
00:28:32,920 --> 00:28:36,595
- Where are you?
- I could get you down with the rope.

276
00:28:38,240 --> 00:28:41,710
- Where is he?
- I'm over here.

277
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:47,632
- Careful.
- Is the flash on?

278
00:28:57,960 --> 00:29:01,714
Everyone brought
something to The Temple.

279
00:29:01,800 --> 00:29:07,318
Before long Huey and Susan brought
guns they'd dug out from somewhere.

280
00:29:07,400 --> 00:29:09,868
I hope it still works.

281
00:29:10,160 --> 00:29:12,674
Stevie?

282
00:29:12,760 --> 00:29:16,753
We have a new addition over here.

283
00:29:16,840 --> 00:29:20,799
Can you come help look at it?

284
00:29:21,080 --> 00:29:26,200
Wow! You got yourself
a hand cannon there, Huey.

285
00:29:26,280 --> 00:29:28,748
Let me take a look.

286
00:29:28,840 --> 00:29:32,435
I believe this is a 52 caliber.

287
00:29:32,520 --> 00:29:39,517
Which means the bullets are that big.
It's what we call a front loader.

288
00:29:39,600 --> 00:29:44,720
Huey had picked an older model.
Nobody could say it wasn't dandy, -

289
00:29:44,800 --> 00:29:46,870
- as we soon began to say.

290
00:29:47,160 --> 00:29:49,549
Extremely dandy.

291
00:29:49,640 --> 00:29:53,474
Good sport. What's its name?
Is it a he, or a she?

292
00:29:53,560 --> 00:29:58,634
- Oh, it's a he.
- Thought so.

293
00:30:00,440 --> 00:30:03,716
I think his name should be Lyndon.

294
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:07,788
And everything revolved around
you and I, Wendy.

295
00:30:08,080 --> 00:30:11,356
And we kept listening to
The Zombies.

296
00:30:11,440 --> 00:30:14,830
This one's Lee?
Can I hold them?

297
00:30:15,120 --> 00:30:16,519
Yes.

298
00:30:16,600 --> 00:30:23,039
Susan stuck to American history. We
didn't like modern, vulgar weapons.

299
00:30:23,360 --> 00:30:28,878
They were not dandy. She even had
a nice little revolver for Freddie -

300
00:30:29,160 --> 00:30:31,913
- which was later christened Emily.

301
00:30:34,200 --> 00:30:36,839
- Are you sure, Freddie?
- I'm sure.

302
00:30:37,120 --> 00:30:42,752
But he declined. He had a crush on
a gun he'd spotted in a gun store.

303
00:30:42,840 --> 00:30:46,549
$800, said Freddie
which of course meant 80.

304
00:30:46,640 --> 00:30:52,158
None of us had that kind of money.
It was hard on Emily.

305
00:30:52,240 --> 00:30:55,118
But then again, she was no beauty.

306
00:30:58,360 --> 00:31:04,708
We had poetry readings.
And the Dandies made a secret sign.

307
00:31:04,800 --> 00:31:07,553
- You guys want to hear it?
- Yeah.

308
00:31:10,640 --> 00:31:15,270
Lee is cold as ice
Grant is hot as hell.

309
00:31:15,360 --> 00:31:18,830
I think they're both real nice, -

310
00:31:18,920 --> 00:31:23,072
- and I hope it all ends well.

311
00:31:31,480 --> 00:31:34,836
Can you teach me to write like that?

312
00:31:36,320 --> 00:31:38,629
Then we had our inauguration.

313
00:31:38,720 --> 00:31:43,475
Drinking Offley's Invalid Port
the most dandy I could get.

314
00:31:43,560 --> 00:31:47,269
It was terrible, but soon became
part of the rituals.

315
00:31:47,360 --> 00:31:52,275
Stevie suggested appointing me
chief, but I insisted on a vote.

316
00:31:52,360 --> 00:31:57,115
A vote where everyone had a say.
Stevie, Huey, Freddie and Susan.

317
00:31:57,200 --> 00:32:00,351
But even more important
you, Wendy.

318
00:32:00,440 --> 00:32:06,436
Stevie's Bad Steel, Susan's Lee
and Grant, and Huey's Lyndon.

319
00:32:06,520 --> 00:32:10,354
- Hi, Lyndon.
- Hello, Wendy.

320
00:32:11,760 --> 00:32:15,833
Since you brought it up
what about you?

321
00:32:15,920 --> 00:32:18,150
You.

322
00:32:18,240 --> 00:32:22,392
- And Bad Steel?
- You too.

323
00:32:22,480 --> 00:32:25,756
- No doubt about it. You, Dick.
- You.

324
00:32:26,040 --> 00:32:28,713
And Lyndon?

325
00:32:33,120 --> 00:32:37,716
I don't get it.
I can't really say anything.

326
00:32:37,800 --> 00:32:42,112
Just pick him, Huey.
You just ruined the whole thing.

327
00:32:42,200 --> 00:32:47,399
OK, OK... Uhm.
You, too.

328
00:32:47,480 --> 00:32:49,710
- Are you sure?
- Real sure.

329
00:32:49,800 --> 00:32:53,634
- That makes 80 votes.
- Bravo.

330
00:32:53,720 --> 00:32:59,158
OK... the regulations. The most
important thing for a Dandy is-

331
00:32:59,240 --> 00:33:04,439
- never to show off his partner.
Whatever the provocation.

332
00:33:04,520 --> 00:33:09,150
We carry them as moral supports.

333
00:33:09,240 --> 00:33:12,152
That's the most important thing.

334
00:33:12,240 --> 00:33:17,792
They may be carried
but never brandished.

335
00:33:18,080 --> 00:33:21,595
Not one of us were in doubt
about the most important thing.

336
00:33:21,680 --> 00:33:27,152
The reason why our partners could
never be exposed to full light-

337
00:33:27,240 --> 00:33:30,710
- and thereby woken up.
Once awoken, -

338
00:33:30,800 --> 00:33:34,839
- nothing could stop them
from killing.

339
00:33:34,920 --> 00:33:39,869
It was so forbidden to say that word
that we called it "loving".

340
00:33:39,960 --> 00:33:45,512
And loving could never ever happen.
That would be the end of it all.

341
00:33:45,600 --> 00:33:48,751
- Hear.
- Hear.

342
00:33:49,040 --> 00:33:52,715
I'm Patrick Besant-Matthews
a forensic pathologist-

343
00:33:52,800 --> 00:33:55,792
- with a special interest
in firearms injuries.

344
00:33:56,080 --> 00:34:00,915
We're going to discuss how
firearms injuries appear in the body.

345
00:34:02,800 --> 00:34:07,271
The entrance site intersected this
junction between two skull bones...

346
00:34:07,360 --> 00:34:10,750
Maybe he shot from close range.

347
00:34:10,840 --> 00:34:14,515
It has to be close range.

348
00:34:14,600 --> 00:34:18,718
...the base of the
22 rim fire cartridge...

349
00:34:19,000 --> 00:34:23,710
Do you see that? See how fast
it slides straight through?

350
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:28,437
This one coming out
is my favorite.

351
00:34:28,520 --> 00:34:32,115
...someone shoots him
with a military rifle...

352
00:34:33,240 --> 00:34:36,835
It really didn't feel like much.
Much less than a punch.

353
00:34:37,120 --> 00:34:43,195
They'd cut themselves, then tied
leather straps around their balls.

354
00:34:43,280 --> 00:34:50,118
The pain made them stronger.
They would hide in the forest, -

355
00:34:50,200 --> 00:34:54,876
- and then go up to the American
soldiers and cut their heads off.

356
00:34:54,960 --> 00:34:58,714
These warriors would become
practically unstoppable.

357
00:34:59,000 --> 00:35:02,709
That's their testicles
and that's the penis.

358
00:35:02,800 --> 00:35:07,396
Susan, cover your eyes. I don't
know if you've seen a penis before.

359
00:35:07,480 --> 00:35:09,755
I'm sorry I had to show you that.

360
00:35:10,040 --> 00:35:15,876
He being an old Vietnam vet
obviously has the. 45 service pistol.

361
00:35:16,160 --> 00:35:19,436
Everyone loved "guess the gun".

362
00:35:19,520 --> 00:35:24,833
She killed her perpetrator
with a. 44 revolver.

363
00:35:24,920 --> 00:35:28,674
He's gonna go with
the service revolver.

364
00:35:28,760 --> 00:35:30,352
It's a treacherous gun.

365
00:35:30,440 --> 00:35:34,274
Because he's a military man
he'll have the all automatic.

366
00:35:34,360 --> 00:35:36,715
Only this will fit in
her glove compartment.

367
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:41,676
The L1808 polymer appeals to
a more dubious kind of character.

368
00:35:41,760 --> 00:35:46,595
Everyone except Freddie
who watched from the sidelines, -

369
00:35:46,680 --> 00:35:49,148
- fired and fired, and got better.

370
00:35:49,240 --> 00:35:53,518
Everyone carried and nobody knew.
And we all grew.

371
00:35:56,040 --> 00:36:00,875
It was your idea, Wendy, that
I should fire you from the hip.

372
00:36:00,960 --> 00:36:04,999
As aiming was your business
it worked like a dream.

373
00:36:06,920 --> 00:36:08,319
Slow down, Calamity Jane.

374
00:36:08,400 --> 00:36:12,712
Susan had a revelation too. She
made up a new way of shooting-

375
00:36:13,000 --> 00:36:16,629
- called indirect.
She aimed at a hard surface -

376
00:36:16,720 --> 00:36:19,518
- and make the
bullet ricochet to the target.

377
00:36:19,600 --> 00:36:24,310
It was so much her.
Shy but clever.

378
00:36:24,400 --> 00:36:28,837
Finally, when everyone had
given up hope, her mother died.

379
00:36:29,120 --> 00:36:34,399
Susan cried, but I told her now
she could redecorate the store.

380
00:36:34,480 --> 00:36:38,393
I said she was the Dandy
that had grown the most.

381
00:36:38,480 --> 00:36:42,632
- Walk straight.
- Without any eyes?

382
00:36:42,960 --> 00:36:45,872
Come in.

383
00:36:45,960 --> 00:36:49,748
We should probably shut the door.

384
00:36:55,080 --> 00:36:59,710
The smell's gone.
It smells nice.

385
00:36:59,800 --> 00:37:04,635
- Come back here.
- Right here? OK.

386
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:11,791
- I can't wait to show you.
- What are you doing?

387
00:37:11,880 --> 00:37:16,590
- Ehm, what are you...?
- They've grown.

388
00:37:16,680 --> 00:37:22,710
My breasts have grown. You
always talk at The Temple about-

389
00:37:22,800 --> 00:37:27,112
- how everybody's growing
and getting better and better.

390
00:37:27,200 --> 00:37:31,796
And I didn't really understand
but I just...

391
00:37:31,880 --> 00:37:36,795
It's like the mind and body
have worked together.

392
00:37:36,880 --> 00:37:41,715
When I carry Lee and Grant, I feel
so powerful. I feel myself growing.

393
00:37:41,800 --> 00:37:45,634
That was not what I had meant
but she was happy.

394
00:37:45,720 --> 00:37:49,759
Huey too was sleeping with a girl.
There was no stopping him now.

395
00:37:50,040 --> 00:37:54,875
He hit on anything that moved.
